1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,735
This is the Genomic Research Agent

2
00:00:02,735 --> 00:00:06,999
an entry for the AMD AI DevMaster Hackathon, Track 2.

3
00:00:06,999 --> 00:00:10,539
It is an agentic AI for population genetics.

4
00:00:10,539 --> 00:00:15,930
Everything you are about to see runs locally on an AMD Radeon 780M.

5
00:00:15,930 --> 00:00:16,815
No API key.

6
00:00:16,815 --> 00:00:18,102
No network call.

7
00:00:18,102 --> 00:00:19,791
No per query billing.

8
00:00:19,791 --> 00:00:24,297
And every number shown on screen is measured at run time

9
00:00:24,297 --> 00:00:26,389
not printed from a string.

10
00:00:26,839 --> 00:00:30,494
I want to start with verification rather than claims.

11
00:00:30,494 --> 00:00:33,321
There are fifty five automated tests here

12
00:00:33,321 --> 00:00:38,286
and they check real mathematical invariants rather than just whether the

13
00:00:38,286 --> 00:00:38,975
code runs.

14
00:00:38,975 --> 00:00:42,147
The eigenvector equation for the P C A solver.

15
00:00:42,147 --> 00:00:44,561
F S T bounded between zero and one.

16
00:00:44,561 --> 00:00:47,595
Minor allele frequency never above one half.

17
00:00:47,595 --> 00:00:52,836
And agreement between the GPU and CPU implementations of the same statistic.

18
00:00:52,836 --> 00:00:56,215
All fifty five pass, with zero compiler warnings.

19
00:00:56,665 --> 00:01:01,091
Here are six natural language queries running through the agent.

20
00:01:01,091 --> 00:01:06,071
Each one is routed by a custom Okapi B M twenty five kernel that I wrote

21
00:01:06,071 --> 00:01:06,901
from scratch

22
00:01:06,901 --> 00:01:11,604
with bigram features, dispatched as a compute shader on the AMD GPU.

23
00:01:11,604 --> 00:01:15,961
Look at the relevance score printed beside every selected tool.

24
00:01:15,961 --> 00:01:20,111
That means the routing is auditable rather than a black box.

25
00:01:20,111 --> 00:01:23,984
Most agents do this step with a language model API call.

26
00:01:23,984 --> 00:01:27,166
This one does not need a language model at all

27
00:01:27,166 --> 00:01:31,246
so the core function has no network dependency and no cost.

28
00:01:31,696 --> 00:01:33,280
Now the GPU benchmark.

29
00:01:33,280 --> 00:01:38,679
The code explicitly enumerates graphics adapters and targets the AMD device

30
00:01:38,679 --> 00:01:39,903
by its vendor I D

31
00:01:39,903 --> 00:01:45,087
rather than accepting whichever GPU a generic high performance heuristic

32
00:01:45,087 --> 00:01:45,879
would pick.

33
00:01:45,879 --> 00:01:50,270
That matters on this machine, which also has a discrete card.

34
00:01:50,270 --> 00:01:55,526
Every GPU result is cross checked against an independent CPU reference on

35
00:01:55,526 --> 00:01:56,749
every single run.

36
00:01:56,749 --> 00:02:00,277
The maximum observed difference is two millionths

37
00:02:00,277 --> 00:02:03,877
which is floating point rounding and nothing more.

38
00:02:03,877 --> 00:02:09,348
At the larger problem size the GPU path reaches three point four seven times

39
00:02:09,348 --> 00:02:10,500
faster than CPU.

40
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:14,604
And notice that at the smaller size the CPU actually wins

41
00:02:14,604 --> 00:02:18,059
because dispatch overhead has not amortized yet.

42
00:02:18,059 --> 00:02:21,659
That is reported too, rather than quietly dropped.

43
00:02:22,109 --> 00:02:24,458
This is a multi turn conversation.

44
00:02:24,458 --> 00:02:27,706
Turn three is only four words: and its p value.

45
00:02:27,706 --> 00:02:32,473
Term overlap scoring alone has essentially nothing to match on there.

46
00:02:32,473 --> 00:02:36,343
Local conversation memory detects that it is a follow up

47
00:02:36,343 --> 00:02:39,936
supplies the missing context from the previous turns

48
00:02:39,936 --> 00:02:43,460
and it routes correctly back to the selection scan.

49
00:02:43,460 --> 00:02:48,435
Concept questions are handled by local retrieval over a knowledge corpus

50
00:02:48,435 --> 00:02:50,093
compiled into the binary

51
00:02:50,093 --> 00:02:54,170
and it returns passages verbatim rather than generated text

52
00:02:54,170 --> 00:02:58,246
so the answer is grounded in something you can go and read.

53
00:02:58,246 --> 00:03:02,600
That retrieval runs through the same GPU kernel as the routing.

54
00:03:03,050 --> 00:03:04,618
The same tools again

55
00:03:04,618 --> 00:03:09,717
but now against a real bundled slice of the 1000 Genomes Project.

56
00:03:09,717 --> 00:03:14,424
Three hundred real variants across one hundred real samples.

57
00:03:14,424 --> 00:03:16,307
Real biology, real noise

58
00:03:16,307 --> 00:03:22,112
and the full provenance of how that slice was derived is documented in the

59
00:03:22,112 --> 00:03:22,975
repository.

60
00:03:23,425 --> 00:03:27,143
One last thing, and it is the part I care about most.

61
00:03:27,143 --> 00:03:32,474
On synthetic data the permutation test finds sixteen of five hundred markers

62
00:03:32,474 --> 00:03:33,316
significant.

63
00:03:33,316 --> 00:03:36,403
On the real 1000 Genomes data it finds zero.

64
00:03:36,403 --> 00:03:40,471
That is genuine low statistical power at this sample size.

65
00:03:40,471 --> 00:03:44,891
It is not a bug, and I kept it in the demo instead of hiding it

66
00:03:44,891 --> 00:03:50,222
because a test that can never return a negative result is not really a test.

67
00:03:50,222 --> 00:03:55,483
You can verify every claim in this project yourself in about two minutes by

68
00:03:55,483 --> 00:03:57,097
running verify dot s h.

69
00:03:57,097 --> 00:03:58,710
Thank you for watching.
